
Experiment no 8:


<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">

<head>
<meta charset="UTF-8">
<meta http-equiv="X-UA-Compatible" content="IE=edge">
<meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
<title>Mouse Event</title>
</head>
<style>

#home {
height: 70vh;
width: 100%;
text-align: center;
border: 1px solid black;
}

.second {
height: 40vh;
width: 100%;
display: flex;
}

#second_1 {
height: 40vh;
width: 50%;
text-align: center;
border: 1px solid black;
}

.second_2 {
height: 40vh;
width: 50%;
text-align: center;
border: 1px solid black;
}
</style>

<body>
<div id="home" onmouseover="changeBgColor()">
<h1>Home Page</h1>
</div>
<div class="second">
<div id="second_1" onclick="changeFocus()" onBlur="iBlur();">
<h3>Sub_div_1</h3>
</div>
<div class="second_2">
<h3>Sub_div_2</h3>
</div>
</div>

<script>
function changeBgColor() {
let element = document.getElementById("home")
element.style.backgroundColor = "#87CEEB";
}

function changeFocus() {
let element = document.getElementById("second_1")
element.style.backgroundColor = "#90EE90";
}
</script>
</body>
</html>










Algorithm :-
1. Create a home page for a website of your choice using html tags. 
2. Break page into multiple sections using div tag.
3. Add tag inside body tag.
4.Create function changeBgColor() in script tag that changes background color of homepage to light blue.
5. Call this function when mouse is over the home page. 
6. Create another function changeFocus () in script tag that changes color of one of the div element to light green.
7. Call this function when the particular div element is focused
